    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-28T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="444"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d444">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.504/1002: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bursley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-28T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 28, 1943—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>141. Reference is made to the Department’s instruction no. 2402 of January 6,
                    1943 and to the Embassy’s despatch no. 649 [<hi rend="italic">6496</hi>] of
                    January 9, 1943, in reply thereto,<note n="96" xml:id="d444fn96">Neither
                        printed.</note> in reference to the selecting in Mexico of workers other
                    than for agriculture.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador<note n="97" xml:id="d444fn97">Ambassador Messersmith was in
                        Washington at this time; he left Mexico City on January 15 and returned
                        there March 1.</note> discussed this question today with Governor McNutt of
                    the War Manpower Commission, and it was agreed that the Embassy should explore
                    with the Mexican Government the question of an arrangement similar to that of
                    August 4, 1942 to permit the selecting and contracting in Mexico of unskilled
                    workers for employment in the Southwest on railways, in mines and possibly in
                    other industries.</p>
                <p>You are requested to inform the Mexican Foreign Office of this Government’s
                    desire to negotiate such an arrangement in the understanding that if this meets
                    with that Government’s approval a representative of the War Manpower Commission
                    will proceed to Mexico City to take part in the negotiations.</p>
                <p>Please expedite reply.<note n="98" xml:id="d444fn98">In his telegram No. 105,
                        January 29, 1943, the Chargé indicated that the Mexican Government was
                        agreeable in principle (811.504/1043).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
